column8:
It's a wonderful driving destination for Sydney siders albeit 6 hrs. You can drive up to the Pass and relax enjoying the famed panoramic vista from the lookout. Also highly recommend for start hiking Mt Kosciuszko from there, a  18.6km return grade 3 difficulty. It's the highest place of Australia. Equally brilliant alt option is Hiking from sister village, Thredbo. Don't miss it...

column8:
An absolutely stunning place to visit and start a hike from.  The views are out of this world.

Easy to find and toilets are accessible close by.  There is enough room for parking by the side of the road although, during peak-season, you would probably  have to walk a long way from your car to the start of the Main Range Walk which is at the start of Charlotte Pass - it gets very busy that time of the year.

I would highly recommend visiting this region during off-season as the crowds during peak-season are off-putting.

column8:
We are very disappointed with Charlotte Pass. In July, we was purchased few days of daily pass for a trial, and planning spent more days in resort after if service and equipment are okay.
But since the first day, the staff in the OverSnow counter is unfriendly and rude to reply our questions.
Second day even worse, no service just rude. I am asking my friend about Is because of my race or skin colour? otherwise  how come she treat me and white group quite different?
I really have not idea what is the problem that a famous holiday resort has that poor customer service and unrespected attitude? people coming for winter holiday from worldwide, it is a good chance to promote but obviously Charlotte Pass need improve their customer service education.
We are sure of that will NOT visiting again and NOT to recommend to our friends.

column8: You cannot beat Charlotte Pass for its location and staff. I have lived in the area for over 10 years and due to the COVID-19 situation decided to try Charlotte Pass due to their local radio campaign and got some Locals Flexi Passes. Not disappointed at all and will now be only skiing at Charlotte Pass for the foreseeable future. Have a son who has a disability and the staff went out of their way to help him and now he's on the Basin Poma and hopefully he will make it to the top before the season ends! It's all that they say about Charlotte Pass - no crowds, no queues, no cars and you are treated as a person! A great mix of activities from back country through downhill and even cross country back to Perisher. Back up there next week and looking forward to it already!

column8: Visited 28th Nov. Did the beautiful Snow gum boardwalk which only takes around 10 min each way with a lookout at the end. Family and mobile adult friendly with a few steps. Then headed up to the first lookout in the Mount Stilwel track. This one is uphill most of the way with some steep sections but ok if you have moderate fitness levels. Lots of wild flowers starting to bloom and still some snow patches on the mountains. Tip- The snow gums look best after a shower of rain if you can time it for that !!!

column8:
Okay, the weather was gnarly with very low temperatures, a wind that was literally icy cold. Charlotte's was really pleasant. Yep, because when I hiked up to Seaman's Hut it was okay for me, I was dressed up for it, but it certainly wasn't a pleasant sunny walk in the park.
I am not saying it was blizzard conditions, the kind you wouldn't choose to go into, but it was cold,  windy and the ice/snow definitely made an impression on my face when I had exposed skin.
Put it this way, no parent would consider taking their young children on the trail.
My impression:
It was a thrilling experience to hike in that kind of weather, to experience the incredible views of the national park with snow everywhere on higher places and to even have to hike through a distance of 150m of snow to reach Seaman's Hut which is at an elevation above 2000m.
A fire and benches with seats in Seaman's Hut was ideal for a break and for me, a turnaround to trek back the 6kms to Charlotte's Pass.
My feelings are, dress appropriately for the conditions, carry safety gear with you, and ideally have a companion go with you. It was a solo walk back for me on this occasion, yet I wasn't alone on the trail. I carried a PLB, with me, as I do on every hike I go on be it solo or in a group.
I thoroughly recommend hiking from Charlotte's Pass. I have no issues with hiking the same trails again, although I still intend to mix up new trails with older familiar ones.

column8: A rare ski resort in Australia. Beautiful snow scenery and great ski resort. However, it is too expensive and the facilities are old. In particular, the rooms are not soundproof and the facilities are the worst. This is a place where you can just ski and go without internet. Don't expect anything other than skiing.
column11: 호주에서 흔치않은 스키장. 아름다운 설경과 멋진 스키장. 그러나 너무 비싸고 시설이 노후되어 있다. 특히 객실은 방음도 않되고 시설은 최악. 이곳은 인터넷도 않되는 그냥 스키만 타다 가는곳. 스키외에는 아무것도 기대하지 말것.

column8:
It is now 8 pm at night. We are cold and wet and have been trying to get out of here since 3pm. All over snows are broken. I watch many families with young kids under 6. All stuck here and the company doing nothing to help. Everyone is laying on the broken and dangerous pub floor tired and hungry. What a disgrace.
I think we will need to walk the 8 klm out in the blizzard to get out.
I feel so sorry for the helpless staff coping abuse for the lack of maintenance , lack of care.
No good ringing that will take hrs. In my case 8 hrs on the ph just to book.
Jindabyne tip would be run better.

column8:
3 course Lunch was provided with ski ticket.
It was Chinese . There was no first course “ spring rolls “ as they had ran out 2 days previous. There was no fried rice nor desert. Main course Mongolian lamb would not have filled a two yr old. Then the resort had 5 out of 7 oversnow broken down.
Many had known faults for many weeks. The drivers started work at 6am it was 9.30 , they had not had dinner and were still working at 10.40pm with the public safety severely compromised . The one we were in broke down every 400m . We returned to Perisher at 9.30pm.
There were many children tired and crying, it was a nightmare .
I was hoping the police would come and save us.

column8: This resort deserves 0 stars after Sunday the 21st of Augusts conduct. No notice, running 6 hours behind schedule and turning all day trippers away who pre-booked months ahead on the day. Unprofessional and unacceptable. Could've had the common decency to be transparent with the situation and not waiting until the morning of to drop the bad news. Disgusted would be an understatement.

column8: The location is epically beautiful-proud to have this apart of what I call home “Australia” ….but!!!!! The new lease owners of charlottes pass (Kosciusko Chalet/ hotel) have a lot to answer for. Poor service, operationally a disaster, staff are under trained and clearly not enjoying working in this environment. Mountain operation staff are rude to guests and really don’t deserve to be on the mountain with the owners parading around like they are untouchables. Absolute joke. The hotel is falling apart, the cell bar is ruined and stinks. It’s lost its magic that’s for sure. 5stars for the location … -negative 5 starts for the staff and hotel.. such a sad way to see what was such a beautiful place many years ago

column8: We travelled to Charlotte Pass in winter 2022, it's taken me a while to post because to be honest I am still quite upset by our experience. First off, food and accom were great, couldn't fault it at all. But I had 3 x kids scheduled for ski classes and when we got there the classes were huge! We were told that staffing shortages due to covid meant that the ratio of kids to adults had to be increased. My youngest (6yo) who (who had already done some practise runs himself, spent almost an hour trying to do stationary "pizza slices" and even though he'd been doing them on the downhill by himself all morning they wouldn't let him progress unless he could do them on the spot which his little leg muscles struggled to do. The next day was the worst though, because half way through the class time I noticed his class and instructor come by me and I couldn't see my son with them. I looked around like crazy and spotted him at the top of the travellator, on the ground, face in his hands. I raced up the hill in my boots and he was beside himself screaming and crying because they had left him there not noticing him missing and he didn't know what to do or where to go. At the very least at the END of the class you would have thought they'd have done a head count and noticed him missing and I waited for the call- but nup, nothing. I still cannot believe they managed to "lose" my child and didn't even notice at the end of the day.... makes you wonder. Needless to say we will never be returning and my little one never wants to ski again, which is so sad!

column8:
The worst and most expensive 4 hour holiday I've ever been on- if I could give 0 stars I would. My partner and I spent nearly $1000 (!) for lift passes and gear hire for 2 days of skiing, expecting an enjoyable skiing getaway. Instead, it turned into a horrifying ordeal that I wouldn't wish upon anyone.

Our morning started well, making the most of the remaining Spring snow in September. However, after lunch, things took a disastrous turn. While going up on the chairlift for a green run, I missed the exit ramp of the chairlift. I stayed seated thinking I would just be let off by the Operator - but no I ended up tripping a trip wire with my ski. This led to a sudden stopping of the chairlift where I was flung at great force into a platform (photo below). This broke 6 ribs on impact. I then fell over 2m to the ground getting whiplash in the process. I'm not sure why the chairlift was set up like that but my guess is because so much snow had melted by Spring this had created a several metre gap between the platform and ground.

What shocked me even more was the response, the Operator restarted the chairlift as I lay under it waiting for first aid. They then asked me to move "as it was not safe" to be under a moving chairlift (!!)- I had to crawl away as I was in so much pain and there had been no first aid assessment of my injuries and spinal injury couldn’t be ruled out at this stage. Management's response was equally shocking. They seemed unresponsive, indifferent, and took weeks to reply to emails which was surprising given the extent of my injuries.

Exiting a chairlift shouldn't pose a life-threatening risk. If you value your safety I would not recommend going here. I feel "lucky" I only broke six ribs. I think if I'd landed any differently once being flung from the chairlift I could have been much more seriously injured or worse. Terrible holiday.

column8:
Charlotte Pass is a hidden gem in the Snowy Mountains!
Even during peak season, it’s peaceful, car-free, and uncrowded—perfect for a relaxing getaway. The views are absolutely stunning, and the ski runs are ideal for families or anyone wanting a break from the busy resorts. Whether it’s skiing in winter or hiking in summer, the natural beauty here is unmatched. Loved the alpine charm, friendly staff, and easy access via Skitube. Highly recommend for a quiet and scenic mountain escape!

column11:
Charlotte Pass is a hidden gem in the Snowy Mountains!
Even during peak season, it’s peaceful, car-free, and uncrowded—perfect for a relaxing getaway. The views are absolutely stunning, and the ski runs are ideal for families or anyone wanting a break from the busy resorts. Whether it’s skiing in winter or hiking in summer, the natural beauty here is unmatched. Loved the alpine charm, friendly staff, and easy access via Skitube. Highly recommend for a quiet and scenic mountain escape!
